<section id="problem" style="padding: var(--space-2xl) 1.5rem; background-color: var(--color-surface); border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border);">
  <div style="max-width: 780px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h2 style="font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif; font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--color-text-secondary); margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
      The Problem
    </h2>
    <h3 style="font-family: 'Source Serif 4', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 3.5vw, 2.25rem); font-weight: 400; line-height: 1.25; color: var(--color-text-primary); margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
      Spec drift starts at the source and compounds at every step.
    </h3>
    <div style="font-family: 'Source Serif 4', Georgia, serif; font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.75; color: var(--color-text-secondary);">
      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
        Most development processes treat the specification as a starting artifact — written once, then abandoned as code takes over. By the time features ship, the code reflects what was easy to build, not what was originally intended.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
        Adding AI to a broken process doesn't fix it. It accelerates it. Faster drift is still drift.
      </p>
      <p>
        Test-driven and behavior-driven approaches tried to solve this. They work — when someone actually uses them. But writing pedantic tests by hand is tedious. Maintaining spec documents that nobody reads is worse. LLMs remove the tedium; RootSpec removes the drift.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
